04550nam a22007095i 9781400826292DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984684058  a97814008262927 a10.1515/97814008262922doi  a(DE-B1597)446378  a(OCoLC)979578334  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLAW0940002bisacsh04a342.73081 aNielsen, Laura Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLicense to Harass :bLaw, Hierarchy, and Offensive Public Speech /cLaura Beth Nielsen.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Cultural Lives of Law00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Introduction -- tChapter Two. Law and Power in Sidewalk Encounters -- tChapter Three. Experiencing Offensive Public Speech -- tChapter Four. Offensive Public Speech as a Personal Problem, Social Problem, and Subject for Legal Intervention -- tChapter Five. Ordinary Citizens’ Views on the Legal Regulation of Street Speech -- tChapter Six. Power in Public -- tChapter Seven. License to Harass -- tAppendix A. Research Design -- tAppendix B. Questionnaire -- tNotes -- tCases Cited -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffensive street speech--racist and sexist remarks that can make its targets feel both psychologically and physically threatened--is surprisingly common in our society. Many argue that this speech is so detestable that it should be banned under law. But is this an area covered by the First Amendment right to free speech? Or should it be banned? In this elegantly written book, Laura Beth Nielsen pursues the answers by probing the legal consciousness of ordinary citizens. Using a combination of field observations and in-depth, semistructured interviews, she surveys one hundred men and women, some of whom are routine targets of offensive speech, about how such speech affects their lives. Drawing on these interviews as well as an interdisciplinary body of scholarship, Nielsen argues that racist and sexist speech creates, reproduces, and reinforces existing systems of hierarchy in public places. The law works to normalize and justify offensive public interactions, she concludes, offering, in essence, a "license to harass." Nielsen relates the results of her interviews to statistical surveys that measure the impact of offensive speech on the public. Rather than arguing whether law is the appropriate remedy for offensive speech, she allows that the benefits to democracy, to community, and to society of allowing such speech may very well outweigh the burdens imposed. Nonetheless, these burdens, and the stories of the people who bear them, should not remain invisible and outside the debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / Discrimination.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082629240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400826292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400826292.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK